a round and wide sans serif font.
To make the logo stand out, Roboto shouldn't be used anywhere else.
Always save some space around the wordmark when including the logo in your design, as shown in this picture.
Use the black or white wordmark depending on which one works for better contrast.
Isotype is the asterisk from the wordmark, extracted as an icon.
When enclosing, use the inverted version with a dark background preferably, and preserve space around the isotype too, as in the wordmark.
Mixing the icon and the wordmark should respect the same spacing principles applied to both elements.
Logo and isotype are arranged vertically using the same width.
As you may have noticed, the isologotype includes the wordmark with its own asterisk.

The rationale behind that is simple: the isologo is the inclusion of both the logo and the isotype, and the logo should be treated as is. The single word "diaspora" in Roboto font with no asterisk is not Diaspora's logo, and despite of the isologo looking more balanced without the ending asterisk is not enough reason to mutilate the logo in any way.
